## 2. Image Bombs / Zip Bombs

### Decompression Bomb
- Tiny image (e.g., 100x100) with extremely high compression ratio (>500:1)
- Small file on disk expands to gigabytes in memory when decompressed
- Detection: compare estimated uncompressed size to actual file size
- Mitigation: reject if compression ratio exceeds threshold (500:1 configured)

### Dimension Bomb
- Image with extreme dimensions (e.g., 100000x100000) → 10 gigapixels
- Causes OOM during PIL open or downstream processing
- Detection: check width, height, megapixels before full decompression
- Mitigation: reject if width/height > 10000px or megapixels > 50MP

### Aspect Ratio Bomb
- Extreme aspect ratio (e.g., 1x100000) — parser allocates scanlines proportional to width
- Causes memory exhaustion even at moderate megapixel counts
- Detection: check aspect ratio before decoding pixel data
- Mitigation: reject if aspect ratio > 100:1

### PDF Page Bomb
- PDF with thousands of pages, each containing an image
- Causes OOM during page-by-page processing
- Detection: check page count before rendering
- Mitigation: reject if page count > 500

