## 5. Entropy-Based Threats

### High-Entropy Flagging
- Encrypted or compressed payloads embedded in image data have high entropy (>7.5 bits/byte)
- Not necessarily malicious, but suspicious in image context
- Detection: Shannon entropy calculation on raw bytes
- Mitigation: flagged but never blocked (informational only)

### Low-Entropy Stealth
- Attacker deliberately uses low-entropy encoding (repeated patterns) to avoid entropy detection
- Statistical stego detection (chi-square, bitplane correlation) catches this
- Detection: chi-square analysis of paired-byte distributions

---

## 6. Pixel-Level Attacks

### Pixel Value Prefixing
- Specific pixel values (e.g., all-black, all-white) used as markers before hidden data
- Only pixels after the marker are decoded
- Current implementation scans all pixels for printable ASCII — marker-based encoding is invisible

### Out-of-Bounds Channel Access
- Image with declared but absent channel data (e.g., RGBA with zero alpha bytes)
- Parser reads past buffer into adjacent memory
- Mitigation: PIL handles channel validation internally during `open()`/`verify()`

### Colour Channel Manipulation
- Message distributed across multiple channels in a pattern (e.g., bit 0 of R, bit 1 of G, bit 2 of B)
- Single-channel LSB extraction produces garbled output
- Detection: combined RGB interleaved extraction (spatial engine checks RGB combined)

